WEBVTT

00:16.433 --> 00:18.393
And...

00:18.476 --> 00:20.270
c'est fini!

00:26.401 --> 00:29.154
There.

00:30.363 --> 00:33.324
This is a fairly rich dessert.

00:33.408 --> 00:36.035
A light supper,
perhaps a roast chicken,

00:36.119 --> 00:38.371
would make a perfect
accompaniment.

00:38.455 --> 00:40.457
And here I have
a chilled Sauternes,

00:40.540 --> 00:42.542
one of the noble
wines of France,

00:42.625 --> 00:47.547
to drink with our glamorous
mousse à la framboise.

00:47.630 --> 00:50.633
And that's all for today
on "The French Chef."

00:50.717 --> 00:52.302
I'm Julia Child.

00:52.385 --> 00:53.970
Bon appétit!

00:54.053 --> 00:55.680
And cut!

00:55.764 --> 00:58.141
Yes, she's all yours.
Yes, she's all yours.

00:58.224 --> 00:59.517
Yes.

00:59.601 --> 01:02.145
Oh, you've got the spoons
out already.

01:06.566 --> 01:08.067
Mmm.

01:08.151 --> 01:09.527
God almighty.

01:09.611 --> 01:10.904
It's like --

01:10.987 --> 01:13.990
It's like biting into
a raspberry chocolate cloud.

01:14.073 --> 01:15.450
Julia!

01:15.533 --> 01:16.826
Uh, Russ!

01:16.910 --> 01:17.952
Assemble.

01:18.036 --> 01:19.537
To what do we owe
the pleasure?

01:19.621 --> 01:21.122
What's wrong?
Hmm?
What's wrong?
Hmm?

01:21.206 --> 01:23.792
Uh, listen,
things are afoot.

01:23.875 --> 01:26.920
KQED has invited Julia
to do promotion

01:27.003 --> 01:29.380
for "The French Chef" --
eh, radio,

01:29.464 --> 01:32.926
interviews, a TV spot --
in San Francisco.

01:33.009 --> 01:34.344
Oh!

01:34.427 --> 01:35.804
How fabulous!

01:35.887 --> 01:37.180
No.
No, not fabulous.

01:37.263 --> 01:38.765
We have French onion soup
next week.

01:38.848 --> 01:40.141
We have six days to prep.

01:40.225 --> 01:42.185
There's no time --
Onion soup, shmonion soup.

01:42.268 --> 01:44.020
Just reduce it.

01:44.103 --> 01:45.063
That was a soup joke.

01:45.146 --> 01:47.941
Oh, yes.
Eh, it's three days.

01:48.024 --> 01:50.527
Hotel stay, airfare
on their dime.

01:50.610 --> 01:51.986
-Impossible.
-That's what I thought,

01:52.070 --> 01:54.155
but I've got the prepaid
tickets to prove it.

01:54.239 --> 01:56.282
No, I-I mean,
she can't leave right now.

01:56.366 --> 01:59.369
Russell, we are a public
television station.

01:59.452 --> 02:01.579
We do not say no to free.

02:01.663 --> 02:03.832
Then there's Tripp Wilson,
head of programming.

02:03.915 --> 02:05.166
He hates small talk,

02:05.250 --> 02:06.751
hangs up the phone
without saying goodbye.

02:06.835 --> 02:07.877
You'll like him.

02:07.961 --> 02:09.420
And Tate --
I'm drawing a blank

02:09.504 --> 02:11.047
on his last name --
Crawford?

02:11.131 --> 02:13.424
He's the line producer,
and Tom handled the negotiation.

02:13.508 --> 02:15.677
He's very sharp.
Oh, also, the head
of the network --

02:15.760 --> 02:17.846
Al. Take a breath.

02:17.929 --> 02:20.849
Can you write all this
down for me?
Sure.
Can you write all this
down for me?
Sure.

02:20.932 --> 02:24.519
A haiku,
not an epic poem.

02:24.602 --> 02:27.105
No way, not with
Mickey Mantle in the lineup.

02:27.188 --> 02:28.982
He's injured. Again.

02:29.065 --> 02:30.316
And Berra's
called it quits.

02:30.400 --> 02:31.901
The Yankees are toast.

02:31.985 --> 02:33.570
Avis, can I talk
to you?

02:33.653 --> 02:36.239
Sox are gonna win the Series
this year, boys.

02:36.322 --> 02:37.240
I know it.

02:37.323 --> 02:39.117
Hope springs eternal.

02:40.952 --> 02:42.203
Good show today.

02:42.287 --> 02:44.455
It's been so much smoother
having you back.

02:44.539 --> 02:47.584
I hope we can keep it that way
while Julia is gone.

02:47.667 --> 02:49.419
I've broken up the time
Julia will be away

02:49.502 --> 02:52.130
into half-hour and hour-long
segments for us to work through.

02:52.213 --> 02:54.173
The red boxes are hours,
blues are 30 minutes --

02:54.257 --> 02:56.926
Oh, uh, honey, honey, you
remember from the pilot episode

02:57.010 --> 02:58.595
the way Julia likes
to work.

02:58.678 --> 03:01.639
We'll just, you know,
have to feel it out first.

03:01.723 --> 03:03.558
Just a touch
of spontaneity.

03:03.641 --> 03:05.143
I am all for spontaneity,

03:05.226 --> 03:06.936
but can't we schedule
a time for it?

03:08.438 --> 03:09.606
Certainly.

03:09.689 --> 03:11.232
Oh, uh, darling?

03:11.316 --> 03:12.442
Darling.

03:12.525 --> 03:14.027
Blue or...

03:14.110 --> 03:17.196
I'm sorry, Judith,
Paul is trying to blind me.

03:17.280 --> 03:18.698
Can you say that again?

03:18.781 --> 03:20.617
I've scheduled
a book signing for you

03:20.700 --> 03:22.201
on Saturday
for "Mastering."

03:22.285 --> 03:23.703
A book signing?

03:23.786 --> 03:26.623
Well, I do love the way
your scrappy mind works, Judith,

03:26.706 --> 03:29.667
but we purposefully
left Saturday open.

03:29.751 --> 03:32.378
Ooh. No.
Um, tell her it's fine.

03:32.462 --> 03:35.006
We have all day.
We can spare an hour or so.

03:35.089 --> 03:38.134
The book needs you.

03:38.217 --> 03:42.430
On second thought,
count the Childs in.

03:42.513 --> 03:44.265
Paul. Raincoat.

03:44.349 --> 03:46.142
Good. I'll see you there.

03:46.225 --> 03:47.477
Bye-bye, dear.

03:47.560 --> 03:48.645
Bye.
Bye.

03:48.728 --> 03:50.480
Alright.

03:52.565 --> 03:54.150
Uh -- ooh.

03:54.233 --> 03:55.985
That shirt.
Mm-hmm.

03:56.069 --> 03:58.237
You wore it in Marseille
with the buttons undone.

03:58.321 --> 03:59.864
Mm.

03:59.948 --> 04:01.783
After the signing,

04:01.866 --> 04:05.286
I'll take you to this
wonderful gallery in Sausalito.

04:05.370 --> 04:08.665
And from there, we can stroll
to this little bistro

04:08.748 --> 04:11.834
with the most magnificent
artichoke risotto.

04:11.918 --> 04:13.336
Is it artichoke season?

04:13.419 --> 04:15.004
Mm-hmm.
Ooh.

04:15.088 --> 04:16.631
Californian artichokes.

04:16.714 --> 04:18.883
Mm-hmm.
Dripping in butter.

04:18.967 --> 04:22.011
You know, artichokes are
an aphrodisiac.

04:22.095 --> 04:24.681
In ancient Rome, women were
forbidden from eating them,

04:24.764 --> 04:27.350
lest they be tempted
to lift their togas.

04:27.433 --> 04:29.686
Oh, Paul.

04:29.769 --> 04:31.938
Oopsy-daisy.

04:39.946 --> 04:42.156
All these plaid dresses
for summer.

04:42.240 --> 04:44.534
Who wants to look
like a checker board?

04:44.617 --> 04:47.620
Not me.
I am not a game.

04:50.707 --> 04:53.167
How's the San Francisco
trip going?

04:53.251 --> 04:55.628
They're probably
just landing, Mom.

04:55.712 --> 04:58.256
I doubt I'll hear
from them at all.

04:58.339 --> 04:59.716
Unless something goes wrong,

04:59.799 --> 05:02.051
in which case,
it will be my fault.

05:02.135 --> 05:04.387
Don't take your frustration
out on these pleats.

05:04.470 --> 05:06.055
This is your
most flattering dress.

05:06.139 --> 05:07.682
San Francisco was my idea.

05:07.765 --> 05:10.643
I did the work, and they act
like it just happened.

05:10.727 --> 05:12.562
I didn't even get
a thank-you from Russ.

05:12.645 --> 05:15.815
Who's Russ again?
My boss.

05:15.898 --> 05:18.067
Maybe if I were a man
or white,

05:18.151 --> 05:19.652
or better yet,
a white man --

05:19.736 --> 05:21.571
Oh, stop that.

05:21.654 --> 05:24.240
Honey, do you think
it wasn't difficult for me,

05:24.323 --> 05:25.908
or for your father
in med school?

05:25.992 --> 05:27.577
Did you think it was going
to be different for you?

05:27.660 --> 05:28.870
No, I know that
it is difficult.

05:28.953 --> 05:30.329
That is what
I'm talking about.

05:30.413 --> 05:32.248
Even when you agree with me,
you disagree with me.

05:32.331 --> 05:33.791
Your grandma always said,

05:33.875 --> 05:35.793
"I don't want to hear about
how hard it is.

05:35.877 --> 05:39.047
I want to hear what you're
going to do about it."

05:39.130 --> 05:41.007
You know you can't afford
to have a negative attitude.

05:41.090 --> 05:42.467
I don't know why
I ask you anything.

05:42.550 --> 05:44.135
I always know what
you're going to say.

05:44.218 --> 05:45.428
Oh, really?
What's that?

05:45.511 --> 05:48.681
Well, you can't afford
a negative attitude,

05:48.765 --> 05:50.558
a hard head
makes a soft behind...

05:50.641 --> 05:51.768
Mm.

05:51.851 --> 05:53.770
Mm, you just need
to find a good man.

05:53.853 --> 05:57.940
Oh, I knew I had something
I wanted to tell you.

05:59.400 --> 06:01.194
His name's Isaac.

06:22.715 --> 06:24.300
Are we early?

06:24.383 --> 06:26.010
Don't take it personally,
my love.

06:26.094 --> 06:28.679
Californians
don't read.

06:28.763 --> 06:30.848
-Hello.
-Hello.

06:30.932 --> 06:33.476
I apologize for taking up
your Saturday, Les.

06:33.559 --> 06:34.727
Are you kidding?

06:34.811 --> 06:37.271
I'm just trying to avoid
a fire hazard.

06:52.120 --> 06:54.872
Are they all here
for my signing?

06:54.956 --> 06:57.834
I don't think they're here
for the new Hannah Arendt.

07:00.962 --> 07:02.046
Thank you.

07:02.130 --> 07:03.381
Bye-bye.

07:03.464 --> 07:05.341
We absolutely adore
your show.

07:05.424 --> 07:08.094
Oh, thank you, dear.

07:08.177 --> 07:10.012
What recipes
have you tried?

07:10.096 --> 07:11.472
Oh, we don't cook.

07:13.141 --> 07:14.308
Ohh, thank you.

07:14.392 --> 07:15.601
I made this for you.

07:23.985 --> 07:25.862
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

07:33.035 --> 07:34.787
Thank you.

07:34.871 --> 07:36.038
Jul?
Hmm?
Jul?
Hmm?

07:36.122 --> 07:37.915
If you don't mind,
I'm going to sneak out

07:37.999 --> 07:39.709
to the gallery
before it closes.

07:39.792 --> 07:42.503
Oh, Paul,
I didn't realize

07:42.587 --> 07:44.922
it was going to turn
into this display.

07:45.006 --> 07:46.382
It's marvelous, kitten.

07:46.465 --> 07:49.302
I'm just itching to explore.
I'll see you at the hotel.

07:49.385 --> 07:51.387
Yes.

07:51.470 --> 07:53.556
Bye, my darling.

07:53.639 --> 07:55.308
All this, for that?

07:55.391 --> 07:56.893
You didn't
expect it, either?

07:56.976 --> 07:58.186
You kidding?

07:58.269 --> 07:59.896
KQED has no means
of measuring our ratings.

07:59.979 --> 08:01.731
There's been positive
feedback, though.

08:01.814 --> 08:03.191
Nearly 24 letters.

08:03.274 --> 08:05.193
So, when do I get
to meet the boss?

08:05.276 --> 08:06.694
Oh, he's not coming.

08:06.777 --> 08:08.279
Alice Naman?

08:08.362 --> 08:09.906
Alice? Right.

08:09.989 --> 08:11.782
Eh, she's back in Boston.

08:11.866 --> 08:13.409
She works for me.

08:13.492 --> 08:15.369
Helluva salesman.
Relentless.

08:15.453 --> 08:17.121
Thought I was
her special guy,

08:17.205 --> 08:19.707
then I get a call
from Chuck Loudermilk
in Philly, WHYY,

08:19.790 --> 08:21.709
the other day asking about
"The French Chef."

08:21.792 --> 08:23.419
Oh, yeah?
What'd you tell him?

08:23.502 --> 08:24.545
Nothing yet.

08:24.629 --> 08:26.380
Waiting to see
how this goes.

08:26.464 --> 08:27.506
Right.

08:31.594 --> 08:33.471
Sign my spatula?

08:33.554 --> 08:35.681
Ohhhhh! Ha-ha!

08:35.765 --> 08:37.683
James!

08:37.767 --> 08:40.853
Oh, what on earth
are you doing here?

08:40.937 --> 08:42.688
Oh, I happened
to be in town,

08:42.772 --> 08:45.316
and I couldn't resist
coming to see you.

08:45.399 --> 08:48.236
Oh, really,
I can't believe it.

08:48.319 --> 08:49.862
It is an honor.

08:49.946 --> 08:52.281
You know I have a soft spot
for tall cooks

08:52.365 --> 08:53.991
with hearty appetites.

08:54.075 --> 08:55.243
Oh.

08:55.326 --> 08:58.287
James Beard, have you
met Judith Jones?

08:58.371 --> 09:02.500
Not officially, no,
but I am a fan.

09:02.583 --> 09:04.794
Thank you.
Likewise.

09:04.877 --> 09:09.173
Well, I'm absolutely gobsmacked
by this turnout.

09:09.257 --> 09:13.636
San Francisco is a town
of sensualists like us,

09:13.719 --> 09:15.805
unlike dreary Boston.

09:15.888 --> 09:18.307
Beans and cod
and the like.

09:18.391 --> 09:20.142
Ugh!
Ugh!

09:20.226 --> 09:21.936
And I'll prove it.

09:22.019 --> 09:23.729
I'm taking you both out
to dinner tonight,

09:23.813 --> 09:25.523
to my favorite restaurant
in the Bay.

09:25.606 --> 09:29.110
The food is spectacular,
the room is charming...

09:29.193 --> 09:31.487
Oh!
...and the waiters
are delicious.

09:31.570 --> 09:34.156
Oh!
Well, I'm sold.

09:35.574 --> 09:37.952
Oh, Paul, my husband,
is in town with me.

09:38.035 --> 09:39.787
Oh, the more
the merrier.

09:51.090 --> 09:53.175
The artist straps himself
into a harness

09:53.259 --> 09:56.554
and paints upside down.

09:56.637 --> 09:58.139
Remarkable.

09:58.222 --> 09:59.849
Can I help you
with anything?

09:59.932 --> 10:02.268
I'm only here to look
and -- and learn.

10:02.351 --> 10:06.355
I'm -- I'm an artist myself,
from Boston.

10:06.439 --> 10:09.108
I paint standing up.

10:09.191 --> 10:11.527
And, uh, what brings you
to San Francisco?

10:11.610 --> 10:14.322
Are you showing in town?

10:14.405 --> 10:17.450
Uh, I'm here with my wife,
actually.

10:17.533 --> 10:20.369
She's promoting
her television program,

10:20.453 --> 10:22.038
"The French Chef."

10:22.121 --> 10:23.497
Have you seen it?

10:26.125 --> 10:28.127
Julia's weapon of choice.

10:30.713 --> 10:31.839
Oh!

10:31.922 --> 10:33.591
Oh, that is nice.

10:33.674 --> 10:35.885
Avis, you really know your way
around this kitchen.

10:35.968 --> 10:37.345
Well, I should.

10:37.428 --> 10:39.889
I found this house
for Julia and Paul.

10:39.972 --> 10:41.849
You know, it's funny.

10:41.932 --> 10:44.435
I actually met Julia
because of knives.

10:44.518 --> 10:45.895
Street fight?

10:45.978 --> 10:47.396
No.

10:47.480 --> 10:50.441
Actually, she wrote a letter
to my husband about knives.

10:50.524 --> 10:52.651
Bernard wrote a column
for Harper's

10:52.735 --> 10:55.529
about the evils
of stainless steel knives.

10:55.613 --> 10:58.199
Julia felt the same and
wrote to him in solidarity.

10:58.282 --> 11:00.826
I was in charge
of Bernard's correspondence,

11:00.910 --> 11:02.036
so I read the letter.

11:02.119 --> 11:04.080
I loved it so much,
I wrote back to her.

11:04.163 --> 11:06.999
And then we became
pen pals.

11:07.083 --> 11:08.501
For a decade.

11:08.584 --> 11:09.877
Ah.

11:11.837 --> 11:13.964
Then when Bernard passed

11:14.048 --> 11:18.177
and my children started to live
their grown-up lives,

11:18.260 --> 11:21.389
I saw myself
turning into that woman.

11:21.472 --> 11:25.017
Hiding behind the curtains
and watching the neighbors,

11:25.101 --> 11:27.478
waiting for "Perry Mason"
to come on,

11:27.561 --> 11:31.357
telling the grandchildren about
the time she was the May Queen.

11:31.440 --> 11:33.275
Oh, you were
the May Queen?

11:36.487 --> 11:41.492
And then Julia moved here,
and life became exciting again.

11:43.619 --> 11:44.954
Ah!

11:46.622 --> 11:49.500
It's the onions.
I swear.

11:49.583 --> 11:50.960
I never cry.

11:51.043 --> 11:52.795
Oh!

11:52.878 --> 11:54.296
Well...

11:54.380 --> 11:57.383
Now we have enough oignon.
Now we have enough oignon.

11:57.466 --> 11:59.802
It's time for the butter.

11:59.885 --> 12:03.305
Let's go easy --
say, eight sticks.

12:04.807 --> 12:10.938
The tiniest splash
of vermouth, for flavor.

12:14.984 --> 12:16.652
Everything is good here.

12:16.735 --> 12:20.906
Wait till you try the bread.
It is a poem.

12:22.074 --> 12:23.617
Oh, thank you.

12:23.701 --> 12:25.911
I just need to make a quick
phone call, so excuse me.

12:25.995 --> 12:27.788
Just one sec.
Oh!

12:30.791 --> 12:32.543
Oh,
Paul didn't answer.

12:32.626 --> 12:35.171
I so wanted him
to come to dinner.

12:35.254 --> 12:36.839
He'd adore
the ambiance.

12:36.922 --> 12:38.090
Well, you tried.

12:38.174 --> 12:41.135
You just checking in
with your husband?

12:41.218 --> 12:43.220
No, the old
ball and chain.

12:44.930 --> 12:46.724
Hello?
It's Judith.

12:46.807 --> 12:48.350
I'm sorry
for calling so late.

12:48.434 --> 12:51.020
You know I don't sleep.
I've been trying to reach you.

12:51.103 --> 12:52.354
I haven't been back
to the hotel.

12:52.438 --> 12:54.023
It's been a wild day.

12:54.106 --> 12:56.817
Did you wake up at noon,
talk about your feelings,

12:56.901 --> 12:58.777
and have a lunch
of fiddly sprouts?

12:58.861 --> 13:01.113
Not exactly.
I have news.

13:01.197 --> 13:03.324
As do I.
You first.

13:03.407 --> 13:06.827
Julia Child's book signing
was packed.

13:06.911 --> 13:08.162
Overcapacity.

13:08.245 --> 13:10.748
We ran out of copies
of "Mastering."

13:10.831 --> 13:13.292
It was like a Beatles concert
or something.

13:13.375 --> 13:14.668
Sounds noisy.

13:14.752 --> 13:16.462
I, however, can do you
one better.

13:16.545 --> 13:18.756
Your boy Updike
has been short-listed

13:18.839 --> 13:21.550
for the National Book Award.

13:21.634 --> 13:22.885
Holy shit!

13:22.968 --> 13:24.970
Fucking right,
holy shit.

13:25.054 --> 13:26.514
Well!

13:26.597 --> 13:32.061
Well, this is very,
very, very exciting.

13:32.144 --> 13:34.688
Um, congratulations.

13:34.772 --> 13:37.858
Congratulations to you,
my dear.

13:37.942 --> 13:39.068
You did that.

13:39.151 --> 13:40.402
Goodnight.

13:47.660 --> 13:51.288
A bottle of the '55
Saint-Emilion

13:51.372 --> 13:53.123
and two martinis.

13:53.207 --> 13:55.334
Anything for you?

13:55.417 --> 13:57.920
Sorry.

13:58.003 --> 14:00.714
I'm worried
I smell like onions.

14:00.798 --> 14:02.800
I'm worried that I will always
smell like onions.

14:04.051 --> 14:05.719
Eau de French Chef.
Mm.

14:05.803 --> 14:07.304
You'll love it here.

14:07.388 --> 14:09.056
Julia and I come here
all the time.

14:09.139 --> 14:11.934
And Paul third-wheels.
And Paul third-wheels.

14:12.017 --> 14:16.480
So, this can't just be my own
personal "This Is Your Life."

14:16.564 --> 14:18.774
Um, why television?

14:20.484 --> 14:23.153
Do you remember the first
episode of "The Twilight Zone"?

14:23.237 --> 14:25.864
I don't remember any episode
of "The Twilight Zone."

14:25.948 --> 14:26.991
Oh!

14:27.074 --> 14:28.617
"There is a fifth dimension

14:28.701 --> 14:30.869
beyond that
which is known to man.

14:30.953 --> 14:34.415
The middle ground between
science and superstition.

14:34.498 --> 14:37.501
It lies between the pit
of man's fears

14:37.585 --> 14:40.087
and the summit
of his knowledge.

14:40.170 --> 14:43.090
The dimension
of imagination."

14:43.173 --> 14:44.633
Ooh!

14:44.717 --> 14:47.469
I knew from the first episode,
television was my future.

14:47.553 --> 14:49.763
